It is a cross-Harvard\nproject, which
means it crosses the\nvarious schools at Harvard.
It's funded by a four-year grant\nfrom the Mellon Foundation.
And that grant and\nthe project itself
are directed towards\nexploring interdisciplinary
and multimedia methods for\nstudying urban environments,
societies, and cultures across\nthe design disciplines, so all
of the disciplines that are\nhere, but also the humanities
and the social sciences.
And the idea in all\nof this is that,
with a common object of study--
the city-- we can\nbegin to bridge
these disciplinary boundaries\nand learn from each other
and have conversations\nthat are really fruitful.
So for the last\nthree years, we've
been carrying out research\nand site visits, site travel,
with faculty and students\nfrom different schools
across the university.
And we've been focusing\nthat work on four cities,
on Berlin, Boston,\nIstanbul, and Mumbai,
which we see as portals\ninto specific geographies
and urban issues.
They're very different cities\nin very different parts
of the world.
And through that research,\nactually, and the conversations
between these portals,\nwe have been opening up
a very interesting,\nactually, and quite broad
field of comparative\nresearch across geographies
and cultures.
So this is our fourth\nyear of the project.
And our focus has shifted from\nsite-based research and travel
to public programming.
We've had an extensive series\nof conferences and colloquia
and workshops and\npanel discussions
across the year, most of it,\nactually, in this semester.
And in those events, we've\ntried to address major themes
that have emerged in the\ncourse of our research
