So in 1972, Creative\nTime, which was started
by basically artists who were\ninterested in doing projects
in the city--
you can imagine the urban\nenvironment of New York
'72 was so different than\nNew York City gentrified,
nightmarishly overpriced,\nurban development
city that it is today.
Thank you, brah.
So in 1972, artists were\ninterested in using abandoned
derelict spaces to do projects.
So there was projects\nlike Art on the Beach.
There was projects where they\ndid a drive-in theater, which
is totally impossible\nto imagine now,
where you would just\ndrive your car up
and they would project films\non the sides of buildings.
And it was a way to kind of\ninvigorate the landscape.
And through most of the\n'70s and into the '80s,
that was the kind of language\nof the arts in the city,
that it was a kind of space\nto produce ideas and operate
culturally, but also,\nin a kind of ragtag, not
well-funded, guerrilla aspect.
And for most of the first\n50% of Creative Time's life,
it was a shoestring budget.
And it was much more,\nlike, artist-driven,
in so much as it was\nvery performative
and not in your classic\npublic art sense of, like,
pink sculptures.
It was much more like\nguerrilla activity.
And so I say that because\nthat particular period is
so different than the\nworld we live in now.
Not only is New York\ndifferent, but also the kind
