Let me get into about project.
When I first got\nto Creative Time,
the second project I\nworked on was a project
called "Waiting for Godot in\nNew Orleans" by the artist
Paul Chan.
And this is two years\nafter Hurricane Katrina.
And the idea, which\nwas-- you know,
it's funny because it's not\nan original idea at all.
It was totally, overtly\nborrowed from Susan Sontag,
who\'d done "Waiting\nfor Godot in Sarajevo"
during the Balkan Wars.
And Paul was interested\nin doing Waiting for Godot
in the landscape of\nNew Orleans, because he
said that the\nlandscape reminded him
so much of every production\nof Samuel Beckett's play
that he'd ever seen.
But simultaneously, what became\ninteresting about this project,
and which will feed into the\nconversation around community
engagement, was Paul\neloquently stated
that he wanted to do a play\nwith a front end and a back end,
the front end being the\nproduction of a play,
and the back end being the\nproduction of a public.
And when I think about what that\nmeans, which is just to say--
he also said-- which\nI think was great.
He said, we're gonna to organize\nthis project Hezbollah style.
And I said, what do\nyou mean by that?
He was like, well, we're\njust going to go door to door
and ask people what they need.
And that's how we're going\nto organize this project.
And so he was\ntalking about a kind
of Saul Alinsky, leftist\ncommunity organizing model that
is applied to a very traditional\nkind of theatrical production.
That model of\nworking-- and we could
get into that, because\nit's interesting--
has really informed\na lot of the work
I've done since because the\nproduction of the play, to me,
is not just a production,\nyou could say.
It's just a production\nof a theater.
And we worked, actually, with\nthe Harlem Theater Company
to produce it.
And we also benefited greatly,\nbecause the star of our play
was a gentleman named\nWendell Pierce, who was also
the star of the show Treme.
And he featured prominently\nin the show, The Wire.
I don't know if you\nguys have seen it.
Of course you have,\nbecause that's what we do.
But Wendell Pierce also\nbrought that to play.
But the production\nof a play, what
was fascinating-- and to\nme, that's also in some ways
a symbol of the production\nof artwork, which is,
there is an artwork or a sign.
But then the back end\nis the social relations
that are put into play\nto support the symbol.
And the symbol without the\nsocial forces at play, I think,
is something I'm not as\nmuch interested in anymore.
I'm interested in how putting\na sign into the urban sphere
sets into action an opportunity\nto rethink social relations.
We did simple things.
We hosted community dinners.
We did potlucks.
We worked with local\ncommunity organizations.
And the thematic of waiting\nbecame a profound symbol
for many different things that\npeople were working through
in New Orleans, from waiting for\ntheir FEMA trailer to arrive,
waiting for their asthma test,\nbecause the FEMA trailers had
so much asthma problems, waiting\nfor their insurance checks,
waiting for people to\nreturn, waiting for the city
to actually address\ntheir concerns,
waiting for the federal\ngovernment to provide
any kind of aid.
So waiting became an\nimportant metaphor
to deal with this tragicomic\nterrible situation, which
just to say, is still\nentirely unresolved.
The other thing I'd\nsay too-- and it's
important to bear in mind-- is\nthat was a project around race,
obviously.
And the Hurricane\nKatrina is entirely
a story about race in America.
But when we started working\non it, it was interesting,
because people said to us in the\nwhite community of New Orleans,
oh, you're going to do a play in\nthe Ninth Ward of New Orleans?
No white people\nwill see your play.
And then when we talked\nto organizers of color
