But I love this project, so\nI have to tell you about it.
It was a partnership\nwith this place called
Weeksville Heritage Center.
And it is a historic\nAfrican-American community
that was started by a\nguy named John Weeks, who
understood that if\nyou owned property,
you were allowed to vote.
And so he started\nencouraging free blacks
to buy property in this area\ncalled Weeksville in order
to produce a self-determined\nblack community
in the early 19th century.
So in 1968, this place\nhad been lost to time.
And a radical anthropology\ngroup from CUNY
actually had heard about\nthe history of Weeksville
and wanted to find out if the\nactual homes or any legacy
of it was still around.
And so they actually flew\na prop plane over Brooklyn
and found three of\nthe original homes,
because they actually\nwent against the grid.
And so they started a community\norganizing effort and made it
a historical home and community\ncenter called Weeksville.
And we partnered with\nthem to do a project
around radical black\nself-determination.
And the site itself is very\ninvested in that narrative.
But I was also, on\na different level--
and something I'm very\ninvested in in terms of this
